Background

I am interested in movies and their ability to generate revenue. Movie making, though an art, often involves massive business ventures and can be an easy way to lose millions of dollars in investments. Needless to say, being able to predict movie success before the investment is made is a very important, and useful, skill.

One of the main, assumptions up and coming film makers make is that in order for them to make good movies they need money. Ill be testing that notion in this analysis.

Question

Well model that question as follows:

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Revenue} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Budget} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \] Our null hypothesis is that the slope of the regression model,\(\beta_1\) is equal to 0, or in other words that the Budget and Revenue are not related. OUr alternative hypothesis is that the slope is not equal to 0 and, therefore, that there is some sort of relationship between the two factors. \[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \] \[ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \] \[ \alpha = 0.05 \]

Data

For this analysis well use data collect by the The Movie Database. Theyre data has been collected for download at on Kaggle.com as well, click here for the link.

Hide Data

Show Data

library(readr)
movies <- read_csv("../../Data/tmdb_5000_movies.csv")

The Kaggle website notes that budget values that equal zero should probably be treated as if they were null. Ill filter them out of our dataframe and do the same for revenue values.

movies2 <- movies %>% 
  select(
    c(original_title, budget, revenue, release_date)
  ) %>% 
  filter(
    budget != 0 & revenue != 0
  ) %>% 
  droplevels()
datatable(movies2)

Analysis

For this analysis, well conduct test for linear regression, plot a scatterplot and a regression line, check assumptions and find the confidence intervals.

movies2.lm <- lm(
  revenue ~ budget,
  data = movies2
)
plot(revenue ~ budget,
     data = movies2,
     pch = 21,
     bg = "skyblue",
     col = "gray",
     main = "Movie Revenue and Budget"
     )

abline(
  movies2.lm, 
  lwd = 3,
  col = rgb(.4, .4, .4, .2)
)

abline(v=seq(40,120,20), h=seq(40,120,20), lty=2, col=rgb(.6,.6,.6,.2))

movies2 %>% 
  summarise(cor(budget, revenue, use = "complete.obs")) %>% 
              pander( )
cor(budget, revenue, use = complete.obs)
0.7054

Though the dots arent tightly clustered, there does seem to be a consistency in the slope. The correlation coefficient is 0.705, so there does seem to be a correlation.

The estimated slope is 2.96, which is significantly different from zero since $p=0 $ for this analysis. Below I have shown the complete summary of the regression.

pander(summary(movies2.lm))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 902541 3151720 0.2864 0.7746
budget 2.96 0.05236 56.53 0
Fitting linear model: revenue ~ budget
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
3229 132073814 0.4976 0.4974

The mathematical equation for the scatterplot above is

\[ \underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_\text{Mean Revenue} = 902541 + 2.96 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Budget} \] Since our p-value is less than our alpha we can assume that we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis. First, however lets check the linear regression assumptions.

Appropriateness of the Regression

The Regression fails two assumptions. The resideuals in the Q-Q plot are not normal, though the Residuals vs Fitted plot shows that the data is essentially linear. The Residuals vs.Order plot shows that there the error terms seem to be correlated due to the obvious megaphone shape we see there.

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
plot(movies2.lm, which = 1:2)
plot(movies2.lm$residuals, main = "Residuals vs Order")

When checking the confidence intervals below, we see that the intercept varies greatly. Revenue could be anywhere between 5.3 million in the negative to 7.1 milliion in the positive.

confint(movies2.lm, level = .95) %>% pander()
2.5 % 97.5 %
(Intercept) -5277035 7082117
budget 2.857 3.063

Conclusion

More research should be done into the way the data was gathered and perhaps this test should be conducted with inflation accounted for since the data points span from 1916 to 2017. As it stands, since we havent met the assumptions for the analysis, we cant conclude that the more money you put into a movie production the more revenue youll earn. However, further examination might yield more useful results.
